\int\limits_C (x^2+y^2)\, dx + 2xy \,dy
C
x^2+y^2=4
(2,0)
(âˆ’2,0)
x = 2 \cos (t)
y = 2 \sin (t)
t \in [0, \pi]
\begin{align} \int\limits_{C} (x^2 +y^2) \, dx + 2xy \, dy & = \int_0^{\pi} 4 (-2 \sin (t)) \, dt + 8 \cos^2 (t) \sin (t) \, dt \\  & = -8 \int_0^{\pi} \sin (t) \, dt + 16 \int_0^{\pi} \cos^2 (t) \sin(t) \, dt \\  & = -16 + 16 \cdot \frac{2}{3} = \frac{-48+32}{3} \\  & = - \frac{16}{3}. \end{align}
